<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{ha}}}} is used to indicate information about something that has already been introduced
or about which the speaker is expected to know.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{asokoni@KJ{{red}}i@KJ{{book}}gaarimasune. are @EM{{ha}}@KJ{{sino-^character}}no@KJ{{book}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Over there is a red book. It's a kanji book.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{ha}}}} is used to mark a topic, which is then explained or described in the rest of the
sentence.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{private}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{study}}@KJ{{exam}}@HI{{de@EM{{ha}}}}
      @KJ{{in}}@KJ{{country}}@KJ{{word}}@HI{{ga}} @KJ{{learn}}@HI{{emasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      In my school we can learn Chinese.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The sentence pattern @N1{{}}@EM{{@HI{{ha}}}}@N2{{}}@HI{{ga}} selects @N1{{}} as a topic about which a 
quality or property, @N2{{}}, is explained.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{elephant}}@EM{{ha}}@KJ{{nose}}ga@KJ{{long}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The elephant has a long nose.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{ha}}}} is used to indicate a contrast.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kinou@EM{{ha}}}}@KJ{{mountain}}@HI{{ga}}@KJ{{see}}@HI{{emashitaga,}}
      @HI{{kyou@EM{{ha}}}}@KJ{{see}}@HI{{emasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yesterday we could see mountains but today we can't.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When @EM{{@HI{{ha}}}} follows a noun + @HI{{ga}} or noun + @HI{{wo}}, @EM{{@HI{{ha}}}}
replaces those particles. For all other particles, @EM{{@HI{{ha}}}} follows them rather than
replacing them.
</p>

